entry.title: Update `android_ndk` to use new `cpu_features` target
entry.content:
Updates the commit hash of Android NDK to include a change that

replaces the target //third_party/android_ndk:cpu_features with a group

target pointing to the supported //third_party/cpu_features:ndk_compat.

This is a routing change to ensure that there are no future dependencies

on the unsupported implementation. A follow-up change will transition

all references to the old target to the new target.



Other repositories that depend on the r23 NDK will have to address this

when they upgrade to newer NDKs by using the new target directly.

entry.title: Update Private Aggregation contribution bound
entry.content:
Switches the bound from being per-origin per-day per-API, to per-site

per-10 min per-API. Also adds a new per-site per-day per-API looser

bound as a backstop to prevent worst-case leakage. The budget data is

stored on disk in 1440 separate minute-long windows, replacing the 24

hour-long windows before. We do not use separate stores for the two

budgets.



This cl also bumps the storage version, which will raze any existing

stored budgets. It also updates the data deletion logic to handle the

per-site scope, retaining references to the origins that have used it

in the last day to support per-origin deletion. (Note that all data for

the site will be deleted in case of an origin match, however.)



See also

https://github.com/patcg-individual-drafts/private-aggregation-api/pull/45

entry.title: [Extensions c2s] Show reload message in menu for site settings update
entry.content:
When an user updates site settings, the changes are immediate.

However, sometimes a page reload is needed for the changes to be applied

to the page (e.g extension was already injected and the user blocked

extensions). Therefore, we show a reload message in the extensions

menu when a reload needs to apply the updated user site settings. The

reload message is only shown in the tab where the site settings were updated until the user refreshes the page or navigates to another

site. [1]



Known issue:

If another tab was open with the same origin, the site setting will be

updated but the extensions menu will not show the refresh message even

if it needs it (crbug.com/1449066) [2]. Ideally we should cover those

cases, but for now we are matching current behavior for multiple tabs

open for and one of them changes site access. The other tabs

toolbar/menu strings are updated but doesn't match with visible

changes and user is not aware it needs to reload (crbug.com/1449066

[3].

entry.title: Speed up SinCosDegrees() by manual range reduction.
entry.content:
SinCosDegrees() is fortunate enough to take in its arguments in degrees

(360 degrees = 1 turn) instead of radians (2pi radians = 1 turn).

Accurate range reduction in degrees is much simpler than in radians;

45 is a whole number and exactly representable as a double, unlike pi/2.

This means that we can get greater accuracy _and_ higher speed than the

current code of fmod() + internal sincos() range reduction, by doing it

ourselves, mostly branch-free. (In particular, fmod() appears to be very

slow on macOS.) This gives a small boost in MotionMark for the Leaves

and/or Multiply subtests, which both make heavy use of rotate() in CSS.



MotionMark (mac-m1_mini_2020-perf, 95% CI, only significant results):

motionmark_ramp_leaves [ +0.7%, +1.0%]



Same with win-10-perf:

motionmark_ramp_multiply [ +0.6%, +1.9%]

entry.title: [ios] Introduce SyntheticGestureTargetIOS
entry.content:
With this CL, we create a synthetic gesture target for iOS and

add plumbing to inject synthetic events. In order to match the

behavior of other platforms which split up the initial synthetic

WebTouchEvent for a pinch zoom (which has two touches) into

multiple OS-specific events later in the flow, we instead split

this up right out of the gates.



This broke some assumptions in both the unit tests and in the

Android event handling code that needed to be changed.



Some changes were also necessary to force correct sizing during

tests. Without these changes, the embedding compositor would not

produce frames.



Handling of wheel and mouse events is non-trivial and is not

added in this CL.



credit: jonross@ for digging through traces to spot rendering

pipeline issues and dtapuska@ for general guidance on input

events.

entry.title: [DIPS] Handle bounces from links opened in new tabs and windows
entry.content:
This CL adds the ability for the DIPSBounceDetector to detect bounces

that are caused by links opened in a new tab or window. Previously these

weren't detected if they were only server redirects and were only

detected sometimes if they were client redirects.



This CL also adds support for handling redirect chains that have no

initiator for the starting navigation, such as those that occur

when a user-configured start page is loaded on Chrome startup, by

using about:blank as a placeholder for the initial URL in these cases.

entry.title: Decrease WaylandWindowDragController::kHorizontalRailExitThreshold
entry.content:
It was observed that under certain multi-monitor setups, detaching a

tab upwards with touch was making the newly created window disappear

upon drop.



One broken set up is:



- DUT w/ builtin monitor + extended monitor connected

- the user virtually places the extended monitor above the builtin

monitor (in settings > device > displays > arrangement)



Test steps:



- create a browser (eg lacros) window with at least two tabs on the

builtin display (the one placed virtually below in the disposition

setup)

- start dragging a tab upwards to detach it.



The newly created window gets created translucent, which indicates that

Ash understands it as belonging to a different display (in this case,

the monitor virtually above).

Once the user let go the drop operation, the newly created tab simply

disappears.



The problem:



Today, when ozone/wayland receives a wl_date_device::leave event, it

emits a pointer/touch event with a negative Y coordinative to emulate

a drag upwards. In case of pointer, -1 is used, whereas in case of touch,

-1000 is used.

The high value used for touch is intentional, and aims at force an

exit on the horizontal rail mode set in SnapScrollController

(//ui/events/gesture_detection/snap_scroll_controller.cc).



In case there is a monitor virtually placed above, the generated

touch event upon wl_data_device::leave might match the coordinates of that

monitor, and cause the newly created window to be wrong placed into that

display.



This CL adjusts the threshold to be minimally higher than

`GestureDetector::Config::touch_slop`, which controls the horizontal

scroll rails in [1].



[1] //ui/events/gesture_detection/gesture_detector.h



BUG=1430664

R=nickdiego@igalia.com



Change-Id: I89eded1199fe280292472bb3042a15d9409fe32f

Reviewed-on: https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4573506

entry.title: Make the color_value_cache_ cheaper.

Recent CSS Color work made the Color class much more expensive to move

around and compare, which among other things affects

CSSValuePool::GetOrCreateColor(). Change it from a HashMap<> to a new

class, FixedSizeCache<>, which does fewer hash lookups,

is [+0.1%, +0.5%] on MotionMark Leaves on m1-mini-perf,

and [+0.3%, +1.4%] on MotionMark Multiply on win-10-perf.

entry.title: Reland "Reduce string conversion cost in style property setters."
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 04d9f1126b69ccb4ce93c4b3cc3dd04010687e43



v8::String::WriteOneByte() seemingly adds a zero terminator, causing

a one-byte stack overflow. Add the v8::String::NO_NULL_TERMINATION

option to fix the issue.



Original change's description:

> Reduce string conversion cost in style property setters.

>

> When setting x.style.y = z (and we don't hit the special path where z

> is a double), we need to convert z from a v8::String to something that

> we can work with in our C++ parsers. (Unfortunately, it seems we mostly

> cannot just peek into its contents, possibly because it could be moved

> around by garbage collection.) In our existing code, we convert

> implicitly to WTF::String, which causes heap allocation and some hashing.

>

> However, recently CSSTokenizer was changed to support tokenizing

> from StringView instead. In the vast majority of cases, this means

> we don't need to actually heap-allocate anything; we can write out

> the string into a stack buffer and send in a StringView.

>

> linux-perf Pinpoint (95% CI, no PGO):

>

> motionmark_ramp_canvas_arcs [ -1.7%, +0.8%]

> motionmark_ramp_canvas_lines [ -6.0%, +2.2%]

> motionmark_ramp_design [ +0.8%, +5.1%]

> motionmark_ramp_images [ -0.1%, +3.3%]

> motionmark_ramp_leaves [ -0.7%, +1.5%]

> motionmark_ramp_multiply [ +1.7%, +3.2%]

> motionmark_ramp_paths [ +2.2%, +9.2%]

> motionmark_ramp_suits [ +0.4%, +1.6%]

>

> M1 appears to be unchanged, win-10-perf has only small improvements.
